[48,175,177,180,182,185,188],{"class":50,"line":176},4,[48,178,179],{"class":58}," console.",[48,181,69],{"class":68},[48,183,184],{"class":58},"(",[48,186,187],{"class":169},"true",[48,189,190],{"class":58},")\n",[48,192,194],{"class":50,"line":193},5,[48,195,196],{"class":58},"}\n",[17,198,199],{},[97,200],{"alt":23,"src":201},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F7oOeuKd.png",[17,203,204,205,207,208,210,211,213,214,216,217,219,220,222],{},"We can see that ",[21,206,78],{}," is equal to ",[21,209,23],{},". Like I mentioned earlier, ",[21,212,23],{}," is a special value and a special keyword in JavaScript. So ",[21,215,78],{}," equals ",[21,218,23],{},", which confirms that a variable with no assigned value gets ",[21,221,23],{}," by default.",[12,224,120],{"id":225},"not-defined",[17,227,228],{},"Now what if the code looks like this?",[39,230,232],{"className":41,"code":231,"language":43,"meta":44,"style":44},"if(a === undefined){\n console.log(true)\n}\n",[21,233,234,246,258],{"__ignoreMap":44},[48,235,236,238,240,242,244],{"class":50,"line":51},[48,237,160],{"class":54},[48,239,163],{"class":58},[48,241,166],{"class":54},[48,243,170],{"class":169},[48,245,173],{"class":58},[48,247,248,250,252,254,256],{"class":50,"line":62},[48,249,179],{"class":58},[48,251,69],{"class":68},[48,253,184],{"class":58},[48,255,187],{"class":169},[48,257,190],{"class":58},[48,259,260],{"class":50,"line":157},[48,261,196],{"class":58},[17,263,264],{},[97,265],{"alt":120,"src":266},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fo85PkPn.png",[17,268,269,270,27],{},"We get a result similar to before: ",[21,271,120],{},[17,273,274,275,277,278,281,282,284,285,287],{},"So what the heck is ",[21,276,120],{},"? It means the engine can't find ",[21,279,280],{},"var a"," — in other words, the variable was never created. This ties back to the earlier concept of the \"default execution context\". The \"syntax parser\" can't find ",[21,283,280],{}," in the \"default execution context\", so it throws the ",[21,286,120],{}," error message.",[17,289,290],{},"And that's why you'll see this kind of mocking situation:",[17,292,293],{},[97,294],{"alt":295,"src":296},"Ah, ah, ah! You didn't create the variable!","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FrjpHeSm.gif",[17,298,299,300,302,303,306],{},"So here's something we learn: when we write JavaScript, the engine does a ton of stuff for us — hoisting, assigning ",[21,301,23],{},", all kinds of things. But there's one key point to understand — ",[81,304,305],{},"undefined is not equal to null",". Why do I say that? Let's write a snippet and see for ourselves.",[17,308,184,309,312],{},[21,310,311],{},"typeof"," can be used to check a variable's type.)",[39,314,316],{"className":41,"code":315,"language":43,"meta":44,"style":44},"var a;\nconsole.log(a);\nconsole.log('a:' + typeof(a));\n",[21,317,318,324,332],{"__ignoreMap":44},[48,319,320,322],{"class":50,"line":51},[48,321,55],{"class":54},[48,323,59],{"class":58},[48,325,326,328,330],{"class":50,"line":62},[48,327,65],{"class":58},[48,329,69],{"class":68},[48,331,72],{"class":58},[48,333,334,336,338,340,344,347,350],{"class":50,"line":157},[48,335,65],{"class":58},[48,337,69],{"class":68},[48,339,184],{"class":58},[48,341,343],{"class":342},"sTRMh","'a:'",[48,345,346],{"class":54}," +",[48,348,349],{"class":54}," typeof",[48,351,352],{"class":58},"(a));\n",[17,354,355],{},"Now we see a pretty interesting thing.",[17,357,358],{},[97,359],{"alt":23,"src":360},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FvwVdQsW.png",[17,362,363,364,366,367,369,370,372,373,375],{},"In JavaScript, ",[21,365,311],{}," returns the type of a thing — but here ",[21,368,311],{}," returns ",[21,371,23],{},". So once again this confirms that ",[21,374,23],{}," is a special value and type in JavaScript. But there's one thing that's really, really important, and you should never, ever do it:",[39,377,379],{"className":41,"code":378,"language":43,"meta":44,"style":44},"var a;\nconsole.log(a);\na = undefined;\n",[21,380,381,387,395],{"__ignoreMap":44},[48,382,383,385],{"class":50,"line":51},[48,384,55],{"class":54},[48,386,59],{"class":58},[48,388,389,391,393],{"class":50,"line":62},[48,390,65],{"class":58},[48,392,69],{"class":68},[48,394,72],{"class":58},[48,396,397,400,403,405],{"class":50,"line":157},[48,398,399],{"class":58},"a ",[48,401,402],{"class":54},"=",[48,404,170],{"class":169},[48,406,407],{"class":58},";\n",[17,409,410,411,413,414,416,417,420,421,423],{},"This is valid in JavaScript — it won't throw an error, and the engine won't stop you. But in real development this is a seriously dangerous habit. So never set a variable to ",[21,412,23],{}," yourself, otherwise you'll have a very hard time debugging. Normally, when we see ",[21,415,23],{},", we know the variable just hasn't been assigned a ",[81,418,419],{},"value"," yet. But if you manually assign ",[21,422,23],{},", you can no longer tell whether the variable was ever set or not — like in the snippet above.",[425,426,427],"blockquote",{},[17,428,429,432,433,435],{},[81,430,431],{},"Note","\nSo: never manually assign ",[21,434,23],{}," to a variable.",[12,437,439],{"id":438},"image-source","Image Source",[17,441,442],{},[78,443,447],{"href":444,"rel":445},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[446],"nofollow","JavaScript: Understanding the Weird Parts",[17,449,450],{},[78,451,454],{"href":452,"rel":453},"https:\u002F\u002Fhome.gamer.com.tw\u002FcreationDetail.php?sn=4081426",[446],"Jurassic GIF from Bahamut",[456,457,458],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki